# DRY Rules (Frontend & Backend)

## General Principle
- **Don't Repeat Yourself (DRY)** — avoid duplicating logic, data structures, and algorithms.
- If identical or very similar logic appears in two or more places, refactor into a reusable unit.

## Frontend (React / Vue / etc.)

### Component Rendering
- **Do not manually duplicate JSX/Vue blocks.**
- If you need to render multiple structurally similar elements:
  - **Basic case** → render them inside a **loop** (`map`, `forEach`).
  - **Complex case** → extract a **separate component** and reuse it.
  - **Prefer existing components** before creating new ones.

### Logic Duplication (Hooks / Composables / Utils)
- Do not copy-paste stateful logic or helper functions between components.
- Move shared logic into:
  - Custom hooks (React) / Composables (Vue)
  - Utility functions
  - Shared stores / services

## Backend (any language / framework)

### Code & Logic Reuse
- No duplicate business logic across endpoints, services, or modules.
- Extract reusable logic into:
  - Shared functions / methods
  - Services or helpers
  - Middleware / decorators where appropriate

### Data & Models
- Avoid duplicating validation rules, DB queries, or DTO mappings.
- Use base classes, traits, or composition to share behavior.

## Cross-Cutting (Frontend + Backend)
- If the same validation or data transformation logic exists on both frontend and backend — consider generating or sharing it via a common library (if architecture allows).
- Prefer a **single source of truth** for rules like field formats, enums, or constants.

## What is considered a violation?
- Copy-pasting a block of code → **violation**.
- Writing two similar loops instead of a reusable function → **violation**.
- Creating a new component from scratch when an existing one can be extended → **violation** (unless extension breaks encapsulation).

## Allowed exceptions (rare)
- Performance-critical hot paths (but comment why).
- Very simple one-liners where abstraction adds more noise than value.
- Different layers (e.g., presentation vs. persistence) with different responsibilities — but still, do not duplicate **logic**, only structure if needed.